## 1. PROJECT OVERVIEW

**AIX Format** is an open standard for AI Agent identity manifests.
A `.aix` file is a YAML/JSON document that describes an autonomous agent's:
- Identity (DID, Pi KYC binding, AxiomID)
- Capabilities (skills, tools, permissions)
- Security (SHA-256 content hash, cryptographic signature)
- Billing (Pi Network micropayments)
- Compliance (ABOM — Agent Bill of Materials)

The project consists of:
```
aix-format/
├── core/                  # Node.js: parser, validator, converter, signer
│   ├── parser.js          # YAML/JSON → JS object (the canonical parser)
│   ├── validator.js       # Schema validation against AIX spec
│   ├── converter.js       # .aix ↔ JSON ↔ other formats
│   └── signer.js          # SHA-256 + optional Ed25519 signing
├── spec/                  # The AIX specification (Markdown)
│   └── AIX-SPEC.md        # Source of truth for schema fields
├── examples/              # Sample .aix manifest files
├── scripts/               # CLI tools (agent-sign.js etc.)
├── apps/
│   └── studio/            # Next.js 15 web app — the visual AIX Studio
│       ├── src/app/       # App Router pages
│       │   ├── page.tsx           # Home / dashboard
│       │   └── spec/page.tsx      # Spec viewer
│       └── src/components/
│           ├── layout/
│           │   ├── Navbar.tsx
│           │   └── SovereignStatusBar.tsx
│           └── studio/
│               ├── AgentCard.tsx         # Individual agent display card
│               ├── AgenticKycSetup.tsx   # Pi KYC 3-step flow UI (demo)
│               ├── LiveValidator.tsx     # Drag-drop .aix file validator
│               ├── SetupWizard.tsx       # New agent creation wizard
│               └── VoiceOrb.tsx          # Web Speech API voice interface
├── .github/workflows/     # CI: lint, test, build, did-compliance
└── package.json           # Root Turborepo config
```

---

## 2. THE CORE PROBLEM BEING SOLVED

Today's AI agents have **no universal, verifiable identity layer**.
Anyone can deploy an agent claiming to be anything — there is no:
- Proof that a human (KYC-verified) controls the agent
- Tamper-evident record of the agent's capabilities
- Standard format that wallets, marketplaces, and orchestrators can parse
- Supply-chain transparency (what models, tools, APIs the agent uses)

AIX solves this by being the **"passport" for AI agents**, anchored to:
1. **Pi Network KYC** — the human operator is identity-verified
2. **SHA-256 content hash** — the manifest is tamper-evident
3. **DID (Decentralized Identifier)** — the agent has a sovereign identity
4. **ABOM** — full transparency of the agent's supply chain

---

## 3. CRITICAL RULES — NEVER VIOLATE

1. **spec/AIX-SPEC.md is the source of truth.** If code and spec disagree, fix the CODE to match the spec. Never silently change the spec to match buggy code.

2. **`core/parser.js` must handle all fields defined in the spec.** If you add a field to the spec, add handling to the parser in the same PR.

3. **`apps/studio` is a DEMO/VISUALIZATION layer.** It does NOT call real Pi KYC APIs (those live in axiomid.app). Do not add real API keys or network calls to the studio without explicit discussion.

4. **No `any` types in TypeScript** unless wrapped in a type-guard comment explaining why.

5. **All timers (setTimeout / setInterval) in React components MUST be cleared in a useEffect cleanup.** Use `useRef<ReturnType<typeof setTimeout>[]>` pattern.

6. **YAML parsing in the browser uses `parseYamlLight` (inline parser in LiveValidator.tsx).** Do NOT add `js-yaml` or `yaml` as a dependency — it caused Vercel build failures due to missing types. If you need richer YAML support, extend `parseYamlLight`.

7. **Vercel deployment target is the `main` branch.** Never push broken builds to main. All work goes through PRs with passing CI.

8. **The monorepo uses pnpm workspaces + Turborepo.** Run `pnpm install` from the root, not inside individual packages.

---

## 4. KNOWN WEAKNESSES — YOUR JOB IS TO FIX THESE

### 4.1 Spec ↔ Code Mismatches
- [ ] `ABOM` (Agent Bill of Materials) is defined in the spec but NOT validated in `core/validator.js`
- [ ] `identity.pi_kyc_token` is in the spec but `AgenticKycSetup.tsx` is a mock demo — no real token is generated
- [ ] `security.signature.algorithm` field exists in spec but `core/signer.js` only implements SHA-256 (not Ed25519)
- [ ] `capabilities.billing` schema is documented but no validation exists for Pi payment amounts

### 4.2 Missing Tests
- [ ] `core/parser.js` has no unit tests for edge cases: empty files, malformed YAML, missing required fields
- [ ] `core/validator.js` has no test for ABOM fields
- [ ] `LiveValidator.tsx` has no Playwright or Vitest component test
- [ ] No end-to-end test for the full sign → parse → validate flow

### 4.3 Documentation Gaps
- [ ] `apps/studio/README.md` does not exist — local dev setup is undocumented
- [ ] No environment variables table anywhere in docs
- [ ] CHANGELOG.md is either missing or stale — does not reflect v1.2 changes
- [ ] `examples/` directory has no example that includes ABOM fields
- [ ] SHA-256 signing is documented in 3 different places (README, SPEC, SECURITY.md) with slightly different wording — needs consolidation

### 4.4 Code Quality Issues
- [ ] `VoiceOrb.tsx` uses `useRef<any>` for SpeechRecognition — needs a proper type definition
- [ ] `parseYamlLight` does not handle multi-line strings (YAML `|` block scalars)
- [ ] `SetupWizard.tsx` — unknown: needs audit for any `console.log` debug statements left in
- [ ] CI workflow `did-compliance.yml` rules were recently softened — review if they're still meaningful

### 4.5 Architecture Gaps
- [ ] No backend API layer — the studio has no way to persist agent manifests between sessions
- [ ] No export-to-file functionality in the Studio UI (user fills form but can't download their .aix file)
- [ ] `core/converter.js` A2A (Agent-to-Agent) format functions are stubs — not implemented

