## 5. DEVELOPMENT WORKFLOW

```bash
# Setup
pnpm install              # from repo root

# Run Studio locally
cd apps/studio
pnpm dev                  # http://localhost:3000

# Run all tests
pnpm test                 # from root (Turborepo runs all packages)

# Lint
pnpm lint

# Type check
pnpm typecheck

# Build
pnpm build
```

### PR Rules
- Branch from `main`
- All CI checks must pass before merge
- PRs touching `spec/AIX-SPEC.md` require a matching update to `core/`
- Commit message format: `type(scope): description`
  - Types: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`
  - Scopes: `core`, `studio`, `spec`, `ci`, `examples`

---

## 6. KEY DESIGN DECISIONS (DON'T RELITIGATE WITHOUT REASON)

| Decision | Reason |
|---|---|
| YAML as primary format | Human-readable, git-diffable, familiar to DevOps |
| SHA-256 hash = "AIX DNA" | Tamper-evident, no private key required for basic use |
| Pi Network KYC as trust anchor | Only KYC-at-scale network available for agent operators |
| No js-yaml in browser | Missing @types caused Vercel build failures; inline parser is sufficient |
| Next.js App Router | Server components + streaming for spec viewer |
| Turborepo monorepo | Shared tooling, single install, parallel builds |

---

## 7. GLOSSARY

| Term | Meaning |
|---|---|
| AIX | AI Agent Exchange format — the manifest standard |
| AxiomID | The DID identifier generated for an agent (format: `did:axiom:...`) |
| ABOM | Agent Bill of Materials — dependency manifest for an agent |
| AIX DNA | The SHA-256 hash of the canonical manifest content |
| Sovereign Agent | An agent with a verified human operator (Pi KYC) and tamper-evident manifest |
| Pi KYC | Identity verification via Pi Network's Know-Your-Customer flow |
| Trust Chain | The chain: human (Pi KYC) → operator → agent (DID) → manifest (SHA-256) |
| Studio | The `apps/studio` Next.js web application |

---

## 8. WHEN IN DOUBT

1. Read `spec/AIX-SPEC.md` first
2. Check `examples/` for a working .aix file
3. Run the existing tests — if they pass, your change is safe
4. Ask: "Does this change break the Trust Chain?"

